1.3: Subset the data frame to only include monlthy snowfall totals

# base R
s.month <- s3[c(1:12)]

# dplyr: 
s.month <- s3 %>% select(Winter.of:July) 
  # use select() to keep or exclude columns of a data frame
    # keep all of the columns from Winter.of -> July

1.4: Reshape (or rearrange) the monthly data from wide to long format

s.month.gathered <- s.month %>% 
                    gather(key = "month.name", 
                           value = "snow.cm", "Sept.":"July",
                           na.rm = F) %>% 
                     arrange(Winter.of)

1.5: Separate the "Winter.of" column into two year columns: year.1 and year.2

s.month.sep <- s.month.gathered %>%
                separate(Winter.of, c("year.1", "year.2"),

                mutate(year.1 = as.numeric(year.1))

1.6: Convert the monthly column name from characters into numbers. It will be easier to work with for summaries or combining with other data sets.

s.month.num <- s.month.sep %>%
          mutate(month =  sub("Sept.", 9, month.name),
                  month =  sub("Oct.", 10, month),
                  month =  sub("Nov.", 11, month),
                  month =  sub("Dec.", 12, month),
                  month =  sub("Jan", 1, month),
                  month =  sub("Feb", 2, month),
                  month =  sub("Mar", 3, month),
                  month =  sub("Apr", 4, month),
                  month =  sub("May", 5, month),
                  month =  sub("June", 6, month),
                  month =  sub("July", 7, month)) %>%
          mutate(month = as.numeric(month))

fancy <-  ggplot(subset(s.month.clean, month == m), 
         aes(x = year, y = snow.cm)) +

   scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, round(max(subset(s.month.clean,

2.1: Select which snow variables you want to use from our original data frame

s.year <- s3 %>% 
        select(c(Winter.of, Total, on.grnd.)) %>% 
        rename(c(winter.of = Winter.of, total.snow.cm = Total, date.bare = on.grnd.))

2.2: Create a column with day of year for bare ground

s.doy <- s.year %>% 
    separate(winter.of, c("year", "year.2"), remove = T)  %>%
       mutate(year = as.numeric(year) + 1) %>%  # adjusting the winter file
    separate(date.bare, c("day", "month"), sep = "-") %>% 
  mutate(dates = paste(year, month, day, sep ="-"),
         dateyr.bare = strptime(dates, format="%Y-%b-%d"), # from base R
         doy.bare = yday(dateyr.bare)) %>%  #from the lubridate package
  select(-c(year.2, day, month, dates, dateyr.bare))
  
head(s.doy)

## 6 1980          1542      159

NOAA Crested Butte weather data

precipitation and temperature data: accessed on July 10, 2020: https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/cdo-web/datasets/GHCND/stations/GHCND:USC00051959/detail

Goal 3: Summarize and plot summer airtemperature in CB

3.1: Read in the data Note: This presentation does not go through how to check data quality and exploration, although the tools presented here can be used for that! Here, we are assuming all the downloaded data are perfect (which is NOT what you should ever assume)

3.4: Summarize "summer" temperature

cb.summer.temp <- cb.date %>%
                  filter(month == 6 | month == 7 | month == 8) %>%
                  group_by(year) %>%
                  summarize( mean = mean(tmean, na.rm = TRUE),
                    min = mean(tmin, na.rm = T),
                            max = mean(tmax, na.rm = T)) 
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
head(cb.summer.temp)
## # A tibble: 6 x 4
##    year  mean    min   max

3.6: Plot mean, min, and max summer temperature over time

summer <- ggplot(data = cb.summer.gathered, aes(x = year, y = temp), group = val) +
  geom_point(aes(fill = val), alpha =1 , size = 4, pch = 21) +
   labs(x="year", y ="Summer temperature (C)", fill = " ") + 
   scale_x_continuous(limits = c(1974, 2020), 
                      breaks = seq(1975, 2020, by = 15),
                      labels = c(1975, 1990, 2005, 2020)) + 
   scale_y_continuous(limits = c(-3, 28), 
                      breaks = seq(0, 25, by = 5)) + 
   scale_fill_manual(breaks = c("max", "mean", "min"), 
                       values=c("firebrick1", "mediumpurple1", "dodgerblue4")) + 
   theme(plot.title = element_text(color="black", size=10),

         axis.text = element_text(size = 14, colour="black"),
